properties.Summary:
Description: Dangerous wind gusts causing widespread damage are expected or occurring. Very strong winds will continue tonight with gusts reaching 150 km/h in areas prone to enhanced easterlies. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: At 9:40 p.m. PDT, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a severe thunderstorm capable of producing very strong wind gusts, up to nickel size hail and heavy rain. A line of severe thunderstorms just south of Vernon is moving northeastward at 30 km/h. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca.

properties.Title: Hurricane Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hurricane force winds of 90 gusting to 130 km/h at exposed locations except 120 gusting to 150 km/h at the coast with surge of 0.7 to 1.0 m and waves from 4 to 7 m from Hurricane Dorian are expected. Hurricane conditions are expected to develop this morning as Dorian quickly approaches the region. The current track has Dorian moving over the eastern Gulf of St. Lawrence this morning and then over the northern Peninsula this afternoon. Winds gusting up to 150 km/h are expected, especially along coastal areas. ### These winds will topple many trees leading to downed utility lines and extended service outages. Moderate to significant damage to roofing materials, exterior cladding and light structures is likely. This could result in some damage to docks and breakwaters. Shoreline erosion and wave overwash is expected where winds blow onshore. A hurricane warning means that hurricane conditions are expected over parts of the region within 24 hours. Hurricane conditions include (A) sustained winds near 120 km/h or more, and/or (B) significantly elevated water levels and dangerous surf along the coast. Please continue to monitor alerts issued by the Canadian Hurricane Centre and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. Reports of storm conditions and impacts can be emailed directly to NSstorm@canada.ca or by tweeting reports by province using #NSStorm, #NBStorm, #PEStorm, #NLwx, #QCStorm or #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Very high Storm Surge levels are expected to impact parts of the coast. High winds and large waves from Post-tropical storm Dorian have lead to higher than normal water levels this evening near high tide. Water levels at Shediac have risen dramatically to 3.2 metres and 2.6 metres at Escuminac. properties.Title: Tropical Cyclone Information Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: For Post-tropical Storm Dorian. The next intermediate statement will be issued at 06:00 a.m. ADT. Followed by the full information statement issued at 09:00 a.m. ADT. The center of Post-Tropical cyclone Dorian now over the Gulf of St Lawrence near the Magsalen Islands. Dorian will slowly weaken as it moves northeastward into the Strait of Belle Isle later today and east of Labrador tonight. 1. Summary of basic information at 03:00 a.m. ADT. Location: Near 47.4 North 61.7 West. About: Near Magdalen Islands. Maximum sustained winds: 130 kilometres per hour. Present movement: northeast at 41 kilometres per hour. Minimum central pressure: 962 millibars. 2. Public weather impacts and warnings summary. Dorian is currently moving through the Gulf of St Lawrence and is slowly weakening. However it is still producing high winds and heavy rain. Powerful winds and heavy rain will continue to impact parts of New Brunswick, Prince Edward Island, Newfoundland, the Magdalen Islands and the Quebec's Lower North Shore early this morning. Winds over parts of Nova Scotia and southwestern New Brunswick will continue to diminish this morning, and any remaining warnings there will be ended shortly. Large waves and ocean swells will continue along the Atlantic coasts of Nova Scotia, Newfoundland and for eastern portions of the Gulf of St. Lawrence tonight. Elevated water levels and storm surge over parts of eastern New Brunswick will subside this morning. Elevated water levels are expected along Anticosti Island and parts of Quebec's Lower North Shore. Hurricane warnings will be ended early this morning for most of mainland Nova Scotia but will be maintained for Cape breton and western Newfoundland. Tropical storm warnings will be continued for Prince Edward Island, parts of northern and southwestern Newfoundland, the Magdalen Islands and parts of Quebec's Lower North Shore. a. Wind. Many of the regions in and bordering the Gulf of St Lawrence will continue to be impacted by potentially damaging winds this morning. Wind impacts will likely be enhanced by foliage on the trees, causing broken branches, some tree falls, and power outages. b. Rainfall. Rainfall warnings are continued for parts of New Brunswick, Prince Edward Island, the Gaspesie, and parts of the Lower North Shore Quebec. Rainfall amounts of 50 to 100 mm are possible in these regions. c. Surge/Waves. Storm surge warnings remain in effect for the many coastal regions along the Gulf of St Lawrence, as well as portions of southwestern Newfoundland. There will also be rough and pounding surf and large ocean swells, along the Atlantic coast of eastern Nova Scotia and southern coastlines of Newfoundland this morning, where waves of 6 to 10 metres will come ashore. Waves of 4 to 7 metres will impact north facing coasts of the Gulf of St. Lawrence. Note that waves will break higher along some of the coastlines, and dangerous rip currents are likely. Please exercise extreme caution. 3. Marine weather impacts and warnings summary. Hurricane force wind warnings remain in effect for most waters in and around the Gulf of St Lawrence. Storm and gale warnings are in effect for adjacent Maritimes waters, and for Newfoundland marine waters in the path or Dorian. Significant wave heights of 6 to 10 metres are occurring in offshore waters south of Nova Scotia, and these will move into the southwest coast of Newfoundland this morning. Waves of 4 to 7 metres will develop over Gulf of St Lawrence waters this morning. Forecasters: Borgel/Hatt ### Please continue to monitor alerts issued by the Canadian Hurricane Centre and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
